\begin_layout Paragraph
Physics behind the desalination process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum entropy principle requires the density of charges to be more-less
 the same throughout the system medium.
 Since the polyelectrolyte gel has its own charges and its own neutralizing
 counterions, the density of mobile ions (which are able to freely enter
 and leave the gel) in gel appears to be smaller than their density outside
 the gel.
 Therefore the internal solution of the gel has lower density of mobile
 ions than the solution outside.
 In that sense, the gel acts as an osmotic membrane separating solutions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rud2020"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The driving force of the separation is the Donnan potential originated
 from the charges of the hydrogel network.
 The density of mobile ions difference between ions concentrations in the
 internal and external solutions is defined by Donnan law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rud2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{c_{-}^{in}}{\cs}=\frac{\cs}{c_{+}^{in}}=\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\alpha\cp}{2\cs}\right)^{2}}\pm\frac{\alpha\cp}{2\cs}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{-}^{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{+}^{in}$
\end_inset

 are the internal concentration of anions and cations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cs$
\end_inset

 is the salinity of external solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\cp$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are the gel molar density and the ionization degree.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 sign in the formula depends on whether the gel is made of polyanion or
 polycation.
\end_layout

