\begin_layout Subsection
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model our gel as a network of 16 linear polymer chains, each by 30 monomer
 units.
 The chains are connected to a diamond-like polymer network and put into
 a simulation box with periodic boundaries.
 Each unit of the network carries a negative electric charge, which is equal
 to the charge of electron.
 Except the particles of the network, the mobile monovalent ions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\na$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cl$
\end_inset

, are present in simulation box.
 The total electric charge of all the particles in the box is zero, therefore
 the amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $\na$
\end_inset

 ions is bigger than that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cl$
\end_inset

 by the number of hydrogel units, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\gel=16\cdot30=480$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this study is to simulate the process of water desalination
 by means of compression.
 In order to do it we simulate the gel in two ensembles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The first is so called 
\emph on
open system
\emph default
, when the simulation box with gel freely exchanges ions with a big amount
 of aqueous solution of certain constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
And in 
\emph on
closed system
\emph default
, when the gel is in equilibrium with a finite volume of aqueous solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compression of the gel in the open system does not affect the surrounding
 salinity, thus the chemical potential of ions remains constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\muna=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mucl=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Const}$
\end_inset

.
 On the contrary, what remains constant in the closed system is total number
 of ions, that are contained in the gel and in the external volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nna=\text{Const}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ncl=\text{Const}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Open system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We simulate the open system using the grand reaction method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landsgesel2020a,Rud2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This method is a hybrid of molecular dynamics (MD) and Monte Carlo (MC).
 The whole simulation represents a chain of subsimulations of MD and MC
 followed one by each other.
 For MD simulation we used a standard Langevin dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Grest1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which models the mechanical movement of all the system particles.
 Whereas MC simulates the thermodynamic equilibrium with reservoir, which
 exchanges ions with the simulation box.
 The insertion (and deletion) of ion pairs is considered as a reaction of
 creation (or annihilation) of an ion pair 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varnothing\stackrel{K}{\leftrightarrows}\na+\cl
\]

\end_inset

with a reaction constant defined by the chemical potential of ions, 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\exp\left(\muna+\mucl\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

